cs.NI, cs.IT, cs.MM, cs.SY, cs.COM

Reasoning: 
1. cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) - The paper proposes a transceiver architecture for future cellular networks, which involves the use of multiple antennas and smart antenna techniques to improve the spectrum efficiency. This falls under the domain of networking and internet architecture.
2. cs.IT (Information Theory) - The paper discusses the use of single-carrier frequency division multiple access (SC-FDMA) for downlink and successive interference cancellation with optimal ordering (SSIC-OO) algorithm for uplink, which are both related to information theory.
3. cs.MM (Multimedia) - The proposed architecture aims to improve the overall spectrum efficiency per cell of the cellular network, which can have a significant impact on multimedia applications that require high bandwidth.
4. cs.SY (Systems and Control) - The use of multiple antennas and smart antenna techniques involves control of the signal transmission and reception, which falls under the domain of systems and control.
5. cs.COM (Computers and Society) - The proposed architecture can have implications on the societal impact of cellular networks, such as improving the quality of service for users and reducing the environmental impact of network infrastructure.
